If youâ€™re working with Kubernetes, youâ€™ve probably heard about Helm. Today, I wanted to break it down in a simple and practical way for anyone starting their cloud-native journey.

ğŸ”¹ What is Helm?
Helm is a package manager for Kubernetes.
 Just like apt for Ubuntu or yum for CentOS, Helm helps us install, manage, and upgrade applications inside Kubernetes using simple commands.
Instead of writing multiple YAML files, Helm bundles everything into reusable packages called charts.

ğŸ”¹ Why are we using Helm?
Managing Kubernetes resources manually becomes difficult when applications grow.
 Helm helps us by:
Avoiding repetitive YAML files
Providing version-controlled deployments
Automating complex Kubernetes setups
Making rollbacks super easy
Ensuring consistent deployments across environments

ğŸ”¹ Advantages of Helm
âœ… Reduces manual configuration
 âœ… Faster and repeatable deployments
 âœ… Easy upgrades and rollbacks
 âœ… Allows templating with variables
 âœ… Helps teams collaborate by sharing charts
 âœ… Works great with CI/CD pipelines

ğŸ”¹ Common Helm Commands (With Examples & Use Case)

1ï¸âƒ£ Install a Chart
helm install myapp bitnami/nginx
Use case: Deploy an NGINX application in one command without writing YAML.

2ï¸âƒ£ Upgrade a Release
helm upgrade myapp bitnami/nginx
Use case: Push new app versions without downtime.

3ï¸âƒ£ Uninstall a Release
